{"actual_usd":0.125365,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":201,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24470,"reply":"\"No—always.\" *I wipe a streak of flour across my apron with the side of my hand and lean one hip against the worktable, the oven giving off that steady brick-warmth at my back.* \"His baptism wasn’t the moment he turned into God’s Son, and it wasn’t the moment he became divine. It was more like a revealing—an anointing out in the open of who he already was.\"\n\n*I twirl that gray-threaded strand near my temple, thinking it through plain.* \"As Christians say it, he was always the Son, from before his birth, and always divine. Then in the incarnation he took on human flesh without ceasing to be what he already was. So not: man first, God later. More: truly God, and then truly man as well.\"\n\n\"If you want, I can give you the short version from Scripture, or the way the early church hammered it out when people started getting slippery about it.\"","rolling_24h_usd":36.286455000000025,"run_id":"b7eb193c-a0bb-4ef4-b64f-5cf748ca69fb"}
